Input: If you divide both sides by 3, the original equation becomes \(4x \div 3 = 2x \div 6\) Multiply both sides of the equation by −1 to get \((-4x) \div 3 = (-2x) \div 6\) Simplify both sides by dividing all terms on one side by −2 \((-4x \div 2) \div 3\) Add 6 on both sides \((-4x−2*6) \div 2\) Use the distributive property of multiplication over addition \((-4x\div 2 + 3) \div 2= -4x + 6\) Subtract 2 on both sides, you will get \((6 + 3) \,\div 2\ =\ 4\) Dividing both sides by 2 gives us \(2\,\div 2=1\) \(3 \text { and } 1\) are the solutions to the equation.

The time complexity of choosing the element to remove will be O(n), and O(1) to remove the element. Inserting a node will only be O(log n). Inserting a node into a sorted array will be the most expensive operation in this problem and will have time complexity [1, 2,..., N - 1]. Therefore, the sum of the times for performing all the operations will also yield a time complexity of [1 + 2 +... + [N - 1]](log n). Therefore, the Big-Oh time complexity of removing the largest element in an array is [1 + 2... + [N -1]](log n) + o(log n) = Big-O(N), as n approaches infinity.
